\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Parents had divorced before JD born. Saw little of father: electrician, went on polar expeditions. 
\par Of grandparents, only knew maternal grandmother and great-grandmother. Maternal grandfather had been in Indian Civil Service, then railway clerk. Great-gran
dmother had money from land development in Birchington, Kent, but grandmother spent it, eventually came to live with them \endash  not an influence.
\par Mother worked as journalist for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 South London Press}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  and Farringdon Press. When JD 13, she re-married to Tom Alderton, banker: nice, kind and dull. His success due to discretion, made few mistakes.
\par Mother socially striving, worried about going downhill. After re-marriage, had house in country, became Conservative county councillor. Left council in protest at election of first Labour councillor. Good works. Stories of eccentricity. Not close, didn
\rquote t have intuitive understanding of her, and she disappointed that he became academic rather than banker - `a bit infra dig\rquote . But as a child not aware of these social nuances.
\par Two older stepbrothers. One a turbine engineer, died young; the other a naval officer, bird watcher and dinghy sailor.
\par Dame School in Sydenham. Taught to read and add by the Misses Tuck, two unmarried sisters.
\par Dulwich College Preparatory School. No significant teachers there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Christ\rquote s Hospital}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4737478  [1949-56]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4737478\charrsid4737478 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Still angry at how he was treated and ashamed of how he responded. English master, David Jesson-Dibley, `an inspiration\rquote 
. History master Michael Cherniavski `hooked me into mediaeval history\rquote , `a great man\rquote . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7208997 \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7208997 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
 Level History, mainly mediaeval. Loved doing texts. Some significant friends such as Anthony Arblaster, city councillor and Professor of Politics, Sheffield; other acquaintances came later: Alan Ryan, later Warden of New College; Jasper Griffin, classic
ist. Saw themselves as intellectual conspiracy against school establishment, and were friends at Oxford. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 [Oxford, University College, 1956-59] }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4737478\charrsid4737478 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Read Modern History. Awarded Second, 1959.
\par Main university friends two groups: University College group around Richard Ingrams and Paul Foot [satirical/left-wing journalists], with Andrew Osborne (original financier of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Private Eye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
) and John Wells. In Balliol enjoyed the company of Arblaster, in a group including Richard Anthony, Steven Lukes [political philosopher], J. D. F. Jones, later foreign editor of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Financial Times}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , Robin Murray.
\par Taught by David Cox, then assisting Churchill\rquote s historical writing, former Fellow of All Souls, mountaineer, later had polio; Tom Parker, chaplain, tiny, his immense learning impresse
d JD; Tony Firth, laid back, later Registrar at Goldsmiths; Prof Ernest Jacob, All Souls, for mediaeval European history.
\par Parties. Writing for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Isis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , then edited by Paul Foot; their column reviewing lectures was banned by proctors. On fringes of group producing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Parson\rquote s Pleasure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , precursor of }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Private Eye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
, inputting jokes \endash  claims to have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7208997 introduced word \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 pseud\rquote . Taste for satirical humour. Keen on music since school, also from Conrad Russell\rquote s mother. Stepfather liked opera, got hooked on Mozart and Berlioz.

\par Wanted to study politics of mediaeval Florence and immigration into the city. Accepted as postgraduate at LSE where could work his way through. Felt he needed anthropology and German (to read the scholarship). Already had Italian. Went to Munich for some 
months [1961].
\par [1956] had won scholarship to Univ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7208997 ersity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
, asked to defer for two years National Service. Got call-up papers 1956, appealed to be accepted as conscientious objector. Waiting for months. Then met organist, John Webster, very annoyed by JD\rquote s review of concert, but he got JD\rquote 
s matriculation brought forward, so National Service and appeal deferred. Then went to Genoa for eight months, teaching English in a secretarial college and learning Italian. Thus }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7208997 able to take special course on \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Florence in t
he Age of Dante\rquote . Fascinated by politics of feud and consequences of migration. Influence of Conrad Russell\rquote s girlfriend Ruth Finnegan in pointing out relevance of anthropology to these themes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 LSE [1961-66] 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Got accepted by the Post Office as night operat
or on the international [foreign] exchange, using Italian, French and some German. But failed medical exam, had to go into hospital, and never did enter the Post Office.
\par While ill, Paul Stirling wrote offering job as research assistant; worked for him for 
two years, researching together on land reform in Metapontino. Aristocratic landowners had been half expropriated by state but remaining land had been drained and made fertile by the state under Christian Democrats, so became fertile, with new small farms
 built. JD tested questionnaires, and spent time in Pisticci. Gave him a taste for southern Italy. 
\par Got MA. Then found funding from several sources for PhD, 1964-69. [This the basis of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Land and Family in Pisticci}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , 1973] Fieldwork 1964-67. 
\par Paul Stirling had been Oxford classicist, became anthropologist, then lecturer at LSE. Very clever, but undermined by the tragedy of his marriage. They adopted four children, two white, two mixed.
\par Learnt from him the value of showing intellectual disrespect for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9598971\charrsid2895163 elders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  and betters. Meticulously careful. Poor collaborator. Sociability with colleagues a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9598971 nd graduate students. But left \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 a broken man\rquote 
 by marriage.
\par Lucy Mair}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid11545695  [Ph}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
D supervisor],}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid11545695  \lquote wonderful\rquote , outspoken, \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 amazingly sharp\rquote . Very interested in land tenure. Precise wr
iting style. Originally Lecturer in Colonial Sociology/Administration at LSE, kept title, even as Professor. Retired 1965 and wrote seven books summarising different fields of anthropology.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid11545695 In Pisticci went \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
armed\rquote  with patronage of Prof of Agricultural Ec
onomics in Naples, Manlio Rossi-Doria, so had letters of introduction to land reform officials. Got a house in Pisticci, up on the hill, and rented a house in the country. Learnt to pass as a dialect speaker so that he could talk to people in countryside.

\par Went to Land Tax Office making notes about area where he had house, Caporotondo, from 1815 onwards. Became surrogate searcher for people in land disputes, and from this talked about agricultural and kinship relations. Also joined group of young men, his a
ge, who would discuss economic and power relations, in a bar or his house. Had old Land Rover, would help people and chat.
\par Much time in the office of Communist peasant organisation, Coltivatori Diretti, with secretary Giannace, efficient and straight, and Cataldo, town councillor, crooked. Gianacce mediated when people quarrelled; helped people with b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 ureaucracy, phoning on behalf of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
 party members. Parallel Catholic organisation.
\par More difficult to get kinship information in countryside because fewer women aro
und, apart from harvest time. Women also repositories of genealogical information in Libya. Country property usually divided among male heirs, but town neighbourhoods woman-centred, and houses passed down to daughters. In town men moved between neighbourh
oods, in country the women move.
\par Case studies in Caporotondo, a patchwork of small holdings. But peasants wanted land in different parts to cater for varying climate and harvests.
\par Studied a situation of change. New factory in the valley, tractors and rotovators on the land. This very much concerned people, so felt it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 was }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 
ssential to study modernisation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 . Felt t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
at anthropologists such as Julian Pitt-Rivers and Michael Kenny, Catholic traditionalist, wrong to treat communities as if untouched by change. 
\par Visi
ted the new factory and went to see economist and lawyer in Rome, Marcello Colitti, who later worked for ENI. He refused to give him the financial information JD asked for, instead made a present of photographs and lunch. But became friends, had an Englis
h wife, left-wing journalist. Big companies and political corruption.
\par Honour and the family system. His worked came after Campbell, and Peristiani edited volume. But he was new in saying that the important thing about honour is that some people have more th
an others. Later realised that honour is a form of stratification, from which people try to escape. Conference run by Giovanna Fiume. Change in law, motives of honour no longer relevant in homicide cases, but some judges disregard this. Honour is now much
 less significant as a social marker, with increasing diversity of jobs, and changing sexual attitudes. Except in poorest areas \endash  and on motorways. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 Historical case. Idea of being \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 furbo\rquote 
, smart, also important. Distinction between interest and love has been overdone: the heart can often follow material advantage.
\par No section on the Church. Story of Evans-Pritchard coming to speak at Kent; JD told him working in southern }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 Italy but not a Catholic; E-P, \lquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Well, you couldn\rquote t have understood a thing\rquote . But in fac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5527492 t town council had been run by C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
ommunists for 15 years, Church less relevant for his interests. At this E-P feigned deafness. Catholic priests were influential, but no longer keys to the land system.
\par Rocco Mazzarone a doctor, worked in Libya in war and returned to home town, Tricarico, where succeeded in eliminating TB from late 1950s. Interested in Italian anthropology. Supporter of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Partito d\rquote Azione}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
, 1940s, left-wing but not Communist, with Gilberto Marselli and Rossi-Doria \endash  who was later a Socialist senator.
\par Why no women thanked? Two women at agricultural institute at Portici were helpful but not very significant. To form a liaison with a local women would have been complicated but not dangerous. Had a girlfriend in Rome.
\par She was the wife of a famous photographer, got him interested. Took some 500 photos which now digitising. Photographed processions, to see hierarchies in marching order; countrysi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1510570 de; agricultural work; people. \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 I w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1510570 as very fond of a lot of people\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 .
\par First article was on a game,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  passatella}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , drinking and cards, published in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
British Journal of Sociology. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 In this article he disguised the place and people, but subsequently used real names, no pseudonyms.(1)

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 People of the Mediterranean}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , 1977. Wanted to survey, and to celebrate indigenous traditions o
f anthropology. Now thinks, like Michael Herzfeld, that there are no significant underlying theme for the Mediterranean; unlike Goody view of unified culture under Roman Empire which has slowly disintegrated. Jane and Peter Schneider see Mediterranean as 
a melting pot for 4000 years. Too little comparative writing in Mediterranean anthropology, saw his survey as first step towards a comparative anthropology.
\par Book dedicated to Maurice Freedman, Professor at LSE, whom JD liked, sinologist, worked on overseas Chinese. He also thanks Peter Loizos, who he admires for directnesss, and raising new issues, and his disdain for claims of cognitive psychology. 
\par Nevill Colclough was fellow graduate, married school teacher from Puglia, very clever but unfulfilled. Two st
udies in southern Italy, one brilliant on industry in the south, but published by ENI without his consent. JD unwilling to help him sue them. Lecturer at Kent.
\par David Morgan also at Kent, played poker together, died young. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4005998 [Female colleague]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , now }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4005998 anthropologist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  at UCL, smart, scholarly; husband less so, but stuck together.
\par Edmund Leach never a friend, but got on well. Through him, became interested in how earlier socio-political systems survive in modern states. Likes his work on irrigations systems and land rights in Sri Lanka. JD\rquote 
s interest in land rights came from Lucy Mair.
\par 1981 married Dymphna Hermans, graduate student at University of Amsterdam. Dutch disdain for competiveness and success. Didn\rquote t like being wife of Oxford professor. Married until 2002. Three children: one working at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9795293 Oxford college}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 
, one working in hotel, and one being treated for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9795293 [disease]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 .
\par University of Kent, 1966-90}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1510570 ; }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Assistant Lecturer to Professor, 1980.
\par Professor of Anthropology, University of Oxford, 1990-95. Felt it needed
 changing, but not easy. Institute had been neglected under Rodney Needham, should have included new developments in migration studies and gender studies. Human Sciences degree. New joint degree with Archaeology. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1510570\charrsid2895163 Inadaptability}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163  of teaching staff, and very 
poor administration.
\par Decided to get everybody to help wire up Oxford Institute for computers, as a bonding exercise. Interested in use of computers in anthropology since went to coursers on this at Berkeley in 1980-81. Computers extend range of analysis. A
t Canterbury had brought in Michael Fisher from Texas, using systems analysis on Lahore marriage market. Got undergraduates writing programmes. Has used himself for Libyan project and now for history of All Souls. Expands horizons. Wants to work out Libya
n marriage patterns, dowries, etc. Large numbers can be summarised in computer readable form. Compare with earlier pioneering studies of Goodwich, sample of only 15 marriages.
\par As Professor, was Fellow of All Souls from 1990; Warden of All Souls College, 1995-2008.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Libyan Politics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 , 1987. Foreword by friend Michael Gilsenan, but JD thinks this is cool; sees him as self-concerned and too keen on avant garde anthropological analysis,
\par Went to Libya three times, 1975-79. Had visa from Libyan Embassy in London to r
esearch, wanted to study the Zuwaya tribe. Held up in Bengazi for permission. Then at a party met Chief of Police for Eastern Libya, a Zuwaya, who fixed it. Rival Tiboo tribe had been studied by an American woman anthropologist and Zuwaya welcomed their o
wn male anthropologist. 
\par Zuwaya were transhumant people with land in north near the sea, where cultivated grain, and date palm gardens in oases in south, 800 miles away: annual movement between areas. Also were traders with black Africa across deserts. Ital
ians had stopped annual movement, dividing the population, many going into exile. Religious revival movement, Sanusya, in which King Idris involved, with lodges in Sahel and Libya welcoming the Zumaya; Italians against this movement. In Second World War h
alf Zuwaya population moved south to avoid battles, and many enlisted in Sahusya battalion on side of Allies.
\par To study them, travelled with convoys of trucks and stayed with them in oases, Kufra, and Ajdabiya. Researched family and kinship, genealogies, tra
de. In Ajdabiya stayed in youth hostel. In oases, lived in tent. This less disruptive to them than living in a house among them, so that women had to dress differently, etc. Also stomach problems, so wanted privacy himself. Friendships with women impossib
le. Could not get women\rquote s perspective.
\par Tribal histories mythical but powerful. Ernest Gellner underestimated inks between his saints and the government. Tribal leaders also had pragmatic relationships with governments.
\par Chose to work in Libya because wanted to study people who crossed boundaries between Mediterranean and other cultures. Also wanted to know more about social consequences of revolutions: were they worth the disruption? Interested in non-market exchanges. W
a
nted to research poor people, but tribesmen turned out not to be poor. Of trans-Saharan trade routes, from Bengazi safer to study. Algeria more dangerous. Gaddafi able to be against a strong state because of his oil wealth: succeeded where Thatcher failed
.
\par Very difficult to get information on family and inheritance comparable with Pisticci. The marriage and divorce papers existed but seemed less credible. Needed access to women for that information. Also land and water rights fluid. This helped migration of
 Zuwaya from north, could claim land rights from remote relatives. Buying big Mercedes trucks shortened travel time, so that wives and children ceased travelling with the men. Using phones and trucks, easier to work alliances through cousins, so that myth
ical segmentary tribal system became much stronger with modern technology.
\par Outside work, interests in music, gardens, museums.
\par Of his work, most proud of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 Land and Family in Pisticci}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2895163\charrsid2895163 ; articles on gift exchange (2); and theory of honour (3). Glad that he was never a structuralist.
\par Of his whole life, best thing the co-operative membership of institutions: Kent, the Oxford Institute, All Souls. Worst thing, having let some people down.
